result.execSummary:
The defendant Anthony D Antoniak was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Anthony D Antoniak is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Anthony D Antoniak was found guilty of Attempt Attempt Armed Robbery [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).
  • Anthony D Antoniak was found guilty of Armed Robbery [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).
  • Anthony D Antoniak was found guilty of Armed Robbery [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).

records.addlTxt: Original PLEA AND SENTENCING HEARING Transcript (28 pages) commencing JUNE 25, 2015 received and filed. kl

Defendant Anthony D Antoniak in court with attorney Christopher Lee Hartley.  Defendant Anthony D Antoniak in custody.  Chad Wozniak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Sentencing proceeds. Statements made by the State, defense and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 2:  The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 10 YEARS, concurrent to Count #4 and Count #7.  
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 5 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 5 YEARS.
Credit given for 134 days time served.

AS TO COUNT 4:  The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 16 YEARS, concurrent to Count #2 and Count #7.
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 8 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 8 YEARS.
Credit given for 134 days time served.

AS TO COUNT 7:  The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 16 YEARS, concurrent to Count #2 and Count #4.
INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 8 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 8 YEARS.
Credit given for 134 days time served.

Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.
Court finds defendant is eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION (AS TO COUNTS 2, 4, & 7):
* Comply with the standard rules of extended supervision.
* No contact with the victims.
* No contact with the co-actors.
* Cooperate and participate with an AODA assessment and follow any recommended treatment.
* Maintain absolute sobriety and submit to random urine screens.
* PAY the balance of all applicable court costs, fees, and surcharges.  The Court ordered that all court costs, fees, and surcharges be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.
* Provide a DNA sample and PAY DNA surcharge.  The Court ordered that the DNA surcharge be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision. DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is to convert to a civil judgment.

OTHER COURT ORDERS:
* Court ordered restitution set at ZERO.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.  
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
Appeal rights given.

  Court ordered defendant REMANDED into the custody of the Milwaukee County Sheriff's Department.

Defendant Anthony D Antoniak in court with attorney Christopher Lee Hartley.  Defendant Anthony D Antoniak in custody.  Chad Wozniak appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

AS TO COUNTS 2, 4, & 7:    Defendant changes plea to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Defendant is advised he is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms. Defendant is advised he is unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored. Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  

Upon State's motion and pursuant to negotiations, Court ordered Count #s 1, 3, 5, 6, and 8 dismissed outright.
